<html>
<body>
<div>
<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Welcome
back!<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>For
day 2 of the StackAware vulnerability management course, we're going to look at
how to tackle the problem of vulnerability overload we explored in <a
href="https://docs.google.com/document/d/1-edxY9QbRjGWV2UHilmEqf9ClWrCNL_qVyZJZ3cywdc/edit#heading=h.r5nne8ppenu2"><span
style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span>day 1<span style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></a>.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>It
all begins with a risk-based approach.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;
mso-outline-level:3'><b><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Vulnerability management is risk
management<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If
patching software or otherwise fixing a vulnerability is easy to do, then just
do it! No need to worry much about prioritization if it's as easy as updating
your iPhone.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Unfortunately,
for most businesses, it's not this simple.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Legacy
applications, complex tech stacks, and concerns about downtime mean that you
can't constantly be updating every system in your network. So you need to make
tough decisions.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The
key here is trading off risk vs. reward.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Vulnerabilities
can create the risk of suffering a data breach or other cybersecurity incident.
But your business needs to make revenue (the reward), so you usually can't
knock a critical system offline to patch everything immediately.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Understanding
which of the four risk management <a
href="https://www.blog.deploy-securely.com/p/the-four-horsemen-of-risk-management"><span
style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span>actions<span style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></a>
(mitigate, transfer, avoid, and accept) makes the most sense requires an
understanding of the financial value to be gained (or preserved) in each case.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>That's
where quantitative analysis comes in; you need to put a dollar value on the
risk posed by each vulnerability.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Attackers
don't care how many &quot;criticals&quot; you remediated this month and neither
should your business leadership. So take CVSS and just throw it out the window
right now.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If
you absolutely insist on using a non-quantitative approach, then check out <a
href="https://www.blog.deploy-securely.com/p/a-somewhat-dreadful-vulnerability"><span
style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span>DREAD<span style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></a>
or the Microsoft SDL <a
href="https://www.blog.deploy-securely.com/p/hurdling-the-bug-bar"><span
style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span>Bug Bar<span style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></a>.
But I won't be going deep on these in this course.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;
mso-outline-level:3'><b><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>The cyber risk management formula<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>There
are many different ways you can get the financial value of a vulnerability and
there are already some great existing frameworks such as the <a
href="https://www.fairinstitute.org/"><span style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span>FAIR
method<span style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></a> and the <a
href="https://www.amazon.com/How-Measure-Anything-Cybersecurity-Risk/dp/1536669741"><span
style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span>Hubbard/Seiersen<span style='font-size:
1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></a> approach.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>While
these techniques are relatively complex, you can really <a
href="https://www.blog.deploy-securely.com/p/how-much-will-exploitation-of-a-critical"><span
style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span>boil<span style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></a>
them down to:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New";mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Annual
risk = annual frequency of cyber incident happening x financial impact of it
happening</span><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:
"Times New Roman"'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>A
more technical way of saying this is:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New";mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Annual
loss expectancy (dollars per yer) = annual rate of occurrence (number of times
per year) x single loss expectancy (dollars)</span><span style='font-family:
"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>To
abbreviate:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New";mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>ALE
($/yr) = ARO (times/year) x SLE ($)</span><span style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Note
that ARO can (and generally should be!) less than 1, indicating that most
incidents happen less frequently than once a year.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Additionally,
it is possible to break down SLE further:<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-size:10.0pt;font-family:"Courier New";mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>SLE
= asset value ($) x exposure factor (percentage)</span><span style='font-family:
"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'><o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Since
not every attack or event would necessarily result in the complete loss of an
asset, we may need to scale the SLE by an appropriate value. That's the
exposure factor. This will come into play in the next lesson when looking at
some more advanced methods for calculating risk.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto;
mso-outline-level:3'><b><span style='font-size:13.5pt;font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;
mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Applying this to the real world, and
a caveat<o:p></o:p></span></b></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>&quot;So
what do I do with this formula?&quot; you might reasonably ask.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>I
agree that the devil is in the details with these types of things, so stay
tuned for the next lesson. In it, I'll explore three different methods for
implementing it in real-world situations.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Before
then, though, I need make an important point. Critics of quantitative cyber
risk management will often say &quot;there are too many unknowns to make a
numerical estimate.&quot; And while there are certainly things we can't know,
we do know some things for certain.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>For
example, <a href="https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2021-44228"><span
style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span>CVE-2021-44228<span style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></a>
(log4shell, probably the worst security vulnerability in history) is more
likely to be exploited in the wild than <a
href="https://nvd.nist.gov/vuln/detail/CVE-2017-8283"><span style='font-size:
1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span>CVE-2017-8283<span style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></a>
(which cannot be exploited in the default configuration of Ubuntu, where it is
often found).<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>If
you have a problem with that statement, then I'm not sure what to tell you.
Because you must also believe that there is no way to calculate the odds of me
getting abducted by aliens on the way to work vs. arriving safely after my
morning commute.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>My
point here is that, yes, of course there is uncertainty. And no, we won't be
able to make risk predictions with complete accuracy. You should hedge
appropriately when communicating with others, making clear that what you are
providing is an estimate. This is important when dealing with skeptics who will
claim you are implying an unrealistic level of precision.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>Both
the <a href="https://www.fairinstitute.org/"><span style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span>FAIR
method<span style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></a> and <a
href="https://www.amazon.com/How-Measure-Anything-Cybersecurity-Risk/dp/1536669741"><span
style='font-size:1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span>Hubbard/Seiersen<span style='font-size:
1.0pt'>&nbsp;</span></a> approach use more advanced methods of statistical
modeling such as the Monte Carlo method to better represent this uncertainty.
And you should by all means read their books if you have the time and money.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>But
I'm guessing you signed up for a free email course on vulnerability management
rather than buy some books because you don't have enough of either.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>So
know that, while I absolutely admit that the techniques I am recommending are
not perfect, they are <i>good enough </i>for the vast majority of situations.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>And
certainly better than the status quo of CVSS.<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>So
catch you tomorrow!<o:p></o:p></span></p>

<p class=MsoNormal style='mso-margin-top-alt:auto;mso-margin-bottom-alt:auto'><span
style='font-family:"Times New Roman",serif;mso-fareast-font-family:"Times New Roman"'>P.S.
